üìå Python Set

üîπ Definition
    A set represents an unordered collection of unique elements, enclosed in curly braces {}.
Example:
s = {1, 2, 3}


üîπ Characteristics of Set

Stores unique values only
Unordered (no fixed position)
Does not support indexing
No slicing or skipping
Mutable (can be modified)
Does not allow duplicate values
Can store only immutable data types


‚úÖ Allowed: int, float, string, tuple
‚ùå Not allowed: list, set, dictionary


üîπ Example (Order not guaranteed)

a = {10, 30, 50, 20}
print(a)
Output (random order):
{50, 30, 20, 10}


üîß Set Built-in Functions

1Ô∏è‚É£ add()
      Adds one element to the set.
Example:
f = {10, 50, 9, 19}
f.add(500)
print(f)

2Ô∏è‚É£ update()
      Adds multiple elements to the set.
Example:
f = {10, 50, 9, 19}
f.update([100, 200, 500])
print(f)

3Ô∏è‚É£ pop()
    Removes one random element.
Example:
f = {10, 50, 9, 19}
f.pop()
print(f)

4Ô∏è‚É£ discard()
    Removes an element without error if value is missing.
Example:
f = {10, 50, 9, 19}
f.discard(50)
print(f)

5Ô∏è‚É£ remove()
      Removes an element, throws error if value not found.
Example:
f = {10, 50, 9, 19}
f.remove(50)
print(f)

6Ô∏è‚É£ union()
      Combines two sets.
Example:
a = {1,2,3,4,5,6}
b = {5,6,7,8,9,10}
print(a.union(b))

7Ô∏è‚É£ intersection()
        Returns common values.
Example:
print(a.intersection(b))

8Ô∏è‚É£ copy()
      Creates a copy of the set.
Example:
a = {10, 50, 90, 100}
b = a.copy()
print(a, b)

9Ô∏è‚É£ clear()
    Removes all elements.
Example:
a = {10, 20, 30, 50}
a.clear()
print(a)
